03973 /**
03974  * cvmx_sli_bist_status
03975  *
03976  * This register contains results from BIST runs of MAC's memories: 0 = pass (or BIST in
03977  * progress/never run), 1 = fail.
03978  */
03979 union cvmx_sli_bist_status {
03980     uint64_t u64;
03981     struct cvmx_sli_bist_status_s {
03982 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03983     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
03984     uint64_t ncb_req                      : 1;  /**< BIST status for IOI Request FIFO. */
03985     uint64_t n2p0_c                       : 1;  /**< BIST status for N2P Port0 cmd. */
03986     uint64_t n2p0_o                       : 1;  /**< BIST status for N2P Port0 data. */
03987     uint64_t n2p1_c                       : 1;  /**< BIST status for N2P Port1 cmd. */
03988     uint64_t n2p1_o                       : 1;  /**< BIST status for N2P Port1 data. */
03989     uint64_t cpl_p0                       : 1;  /**< BIST status for CPL Port 0. */
03990     uint64_t cpl_p1                       : 1;  /**< BIST status for CPL Port 1. */
03991     uint64_t reserved_19_24               : 6;
03992     uint64_t p2n0_c0                      : 1;  /**< BIST status for P2N port0 C0. */
03993     uint64_t p2n0_c1                      : 1;  /**< BIST status for P2N port0 C1. */
03994     uint64_t p2n0_n                       : 1;  /**< BIST status for P2N port0 N. */
03995     uint64_t p2n0_p0                      : 1;  /**< BIST status for P2N port0 P0. */
03996     uint64_t p2n0_p1                      : 1;  /**< BIST status for P2N port0 P1. */
03997     uint64_t p2n1_c0                      : 1;  /**< BIST status for P2N port1 C0. */

04546 /**
04547  * cvmx_sli_ctl_port#
04548  *
04549  * These registers contains control information for access to ports. Indexed by SLI_PORT_E.
04550  * Note: SLI_CTL_PORT0 controls PF0.
04551  */
04552 union cvmx_sli_ctl_portx {
04553     uint64_t u64;
04554     struct cvmx_sli_ctl_portx_s {
04555 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

04558     uint64_t intc                         : 1;  /**< When '0' Intc wire asserted. Before mapping. */
04559     uint64_t intb                         : 1;  /**< When '0' Intb wire asserted. Before mapping. */
04560     uint64_t inta                         : 1;  /**< When '0' Inta wire asserted. Before mapping. */
04561     uint64_t dis_port                     : 1;  /**< When set, the output to the MAC is disabled. This occurs when the MAC reset line
04562                                                          transitions from deasserted to asserted. Writing a 1 to this location clears this
04563                                                          condition when the MAC is no longer in reset and the output to the MAC is at the beginning
04564                                                          of a transfer. */
04565     uint64_t waitl_com                    : 1;  /**< When set to 1, causes the SLI to wait for a commit from the L2C before sending additional
04566                                                          completions to the L2C from the MAC.
04567                                                          Set this for more conservative behavior. Clear this for more aggressive, higher-
04568                                                          performance behavior. */
04569     uint64_t intd_map                     : 2;  /**< Maps INTD to INTA(00), INTB(01), INTC(10) or
04570                                                          INTD (11). */
04571     uint64_t intc_map                     : 2;  /**< Maps INTC to INTA(00), INTB(01), INTC(10) or
04572                                                          INTD (11). */
04573     uint64_t intb_map                     : 2;  /**< Maps INTB to INTA(00), INTB(01), INTC(10) or
04574                                                          INTD (11). */
04575     uint64_t inta_map                     : 2;  /**< Maps INTA to INTA(00), INTB(01), INTC(10) or
04576                                                          INTD (11). */
04577     uint64_t ctlp_ro                      : 1;  /**< Relaxed ordering enable for completion TLPS */
04578     uint64_t reserved_6_6                 : 1;
04579     uint64_t ptlp_ro                      : 1;  /**< Relaxed ordering enable for posted TLPS */
04580     uint64_t reserved_1_4                 : 4;
04581     uint64_t wait_com                     : 1;  /**< Wait for commit. When set to 1, causes the SLI to wait for a commit from the L2C before
04582                                                          sending additional stores to the L2C from the MAC. The SLI requests a commit on the last
04583                                                          store if more than one STORE operation is required on the IOI. Most applications will not
04584                                                          notice a difference, so this bit should not be set. Setting the bit is more conservative
04585                                                          on ordering, lower performance. */
04586 #else
04587     uint64_t wait_com                     : 1;
04588     uint64_t reserved_1_4                 : 4;
04589     uint64_t ptlp_ro                      : 1;
04590     uint64_t reserved_6_6                 : 1;
04591     uint64_t ctlp_ro                      : 1;
04592     uint64_t inta_map                     : 2;
04593     uint64_t intb_map                     : 2;
04594     uint64_t intc_map                     : 2;
04595     uint64_t intd_map                     : 2;
04596     uint64_t waitl_com                    : 1;
04597     uint64_t dis_port                     : 1;
04598     uint64_t inta                         : 1;
04599     uint64_t intb                         : 1;
04600     uint64_t intc                         : 1;
04601     uint64_t intd                         : 1;
04602     uint64_t reserved_22_63               : 42;
04603 #endif
04604     } s;

04616     uint64_t intb                         : 1;  /**< When '0' Intb wire asserted. Before mapping. */
04617     uint64_t inta                         : 1;  /**< When '0' Inta wire asserted. Before mapping. */
04618     uint64_t dis_port                     : 1;  /**< When set the output to the MAC is disabled. This
04619                                                          occurs when the MAC reset line transitions from
04620                                                          de-asserted to asserted. Writing a '1' to this
04621                                                          location will clear this condition when the MAC is
04622                                                          no longer in reset and the output to the MAC is at
04623                                                          the begining of a transfer. */

04625                                                          from the L2C before sending additional completions
04626                                                          to the L2C from a MAC.
04627                                                          Set this for more conservative behavior. Clear
04628                                                          this for more aggressive, higher-performance
04629                                                          behavior */
04630     uint64_t intd_map                     : 2;  /**< Maps INTD to INTA(00), INTB(01), INTC(10) or
04631                                                          INTD (11). */
04632     uint64_t intc_map                     : 2;  /**< Maps INTC to INTA(00), INTB(01), INTC(10) or
04633                                                          INTD (11). */
04634     uint64_t intb_map                     : 2;  /**< Maps INTB to INTA(00), INTB(01), INTC(10) or
04635                                                          INTD (11). */
04636     uint64_t inta_map                     : 2;  /**< Maps INTA to INTA(00), INTB(01), INTC(10) or
04637                                                          INTD (11). */
04638     uint64_t ctlp_ro                      : 1;  /**< Relaxed ordering enable for Completion TLPS. */
04639     uint64_t reserved_6_6                 : 1;
04640     uint64_t ptlp_ro                      : 1;  /**< Relaxed ordering enable for Posted TLPS. */
04641     uint64_t reserved_4_1                 : 4;
04642     uint64_t wait_com                     : 1;  /**< When set '1' casues the SLI to wait for a commit
04643                                                          from the L2C before sending additional stores to
04644                                                          the L2C from a MAC.
04645                                                          The SLI will request a commit on the last store
04646                                                          if more than one STORE operation is required on
04647                                                          the NCB.
04648                                                          Most applications will not notice a difference, so
04649                                                          should not set this bit. Setting the bit is more
04650                                                          conservative on ordering, lower performance */
04651 #else
04652     uint64_t wait_com                     : 1;
04653     uint64_t reserved_4_1                 : 4;
04654     uint64_t ptlp_ro                      : 1;
04655     uint64_t reserved_6_6                 : 1;
04656     uint64_t ctlp_ro                      : 1;
04657     uint64_t inta_map                     : 2;
04658     uint64_t intb_map                     : 2;
04659     uint64_t intc_map                     : 2;
04660     uint64_t intd_map                     : 2;
04661     uint64_t waitl_com                    : 1;
04662     uint64_t dis_port                     : 1;
04663     uint64_t inta                         : 1;
04664     uint64_t intb                         : 1;
04665     uint64_t intc                         : 1;
04666     uint64_t intd                         : 1;
04667     uint64_t reserved_22_63               : 42;
04668 #endif
04669     } cn70xx;
04670     struct cvmx_sli_ctl_portx_cn70xx      cn70xxp1;
04671     struct cvmx_sli_ctl_portx_cn73xx {
04672 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04673     uint64_t reserved_18_63               : 46;
04674     uint64_t dis_port                     : 1;  /**< When set, the output to the MAC is disabled. This occurs when the MAC reset line
04675                                                          transitions from deasserted to asserted. Writing a 1 to this location clears this
04676                                                          condition when the MAC is no longer in reset and the output to the MAC is at the beginning
04677                                                          of a transfer. */
04678     uint64_t waitl_com                    : 1;  /**< When set to 1, causes the SLI to wait for a commit from the L2C before sending additional
04679                                                          completions to the L2C from the MAC.
04680                                                          Set this for more conservative behavior. Clear this for more aggressive, higher-

04711 /**

04714  * This register contains control and status for SLI. Write operations to this register are not
04715  * ordered with write/read operations to the MAC memory space. To ensure that a write has
04716  * completed, software must read the register before making an access (i.e. MAC memory space)
04717  * that requires the value of this register to be updated.
04718  */

04725                                                          non-posted reads, outbound BAR1/BAR2 completions, and inbound CPU completions)
04726                                                          from SLI_PORT_E::SRIO0 and SLI_PORT_E::SRIO1 is placed on. Values 2-15 are reserved. */

04728                                                          non-posted reads, outbound BAR1/BAR2 completions, and inbound CPU completions)
04729                                                          from SLI_PORT_E::PEM0 and SLI_PORT_E::PEM1 is placed on.  Values 2-15 are reserved. */

04731     uint64_t p1_ntags                     : 6;  /**< Number of tags available for MAC port 1.
04732                                                          In RC mode, one tag is needed for each outbound TLP that requires a CPL TLP.
04733                                                          In EP mode, the number of tags required for a TLP request is 1 per 64-bytes of CPL data +
04734                                                          1.
04735                                                          This field should only be written as part of a reset sequence and before issuing any read
04736                                                          operations, CFGs, or I/O transactions from the core(s). */
04737     uint64_t p0_ntags                     : 6;  /**< Number of tags available for MAC port 0.
04738                                                          In RC mode, one tag is needed for each outbound TLP that requires a CPL TLP.
04739                                                          In EP mode, the number of tags required for a TLP request is 1 per 64-bytes of CPL data +
04740                                                          1.

04742                                                          operations, CFGs, or I/O transactions from the core(s). */

04744 #else

06324 /**
06325  * cvmx_sli_int_sum
06326  *
06327  * The fields in this register are set when an interrupt condition occurs; write 1 to clear. All
06328  * fields of the register are valid when a PF reads the register. Not available to VFs, and
06329  * writes by the
06330  * VF do not modify the register.
06331  */
06332 union cvmx_sli_int_sum {
06333     uint64_t u64;
06334     struct cvmx_sli_int_sum_s {
06335 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06336     uint64_t reserved_62_63               : 2;
06337     uint64_t pipe_err                     : 1;  /**< Set when a PIPE value outside range is received. */
06338     uint64_t ill_pad                      : 1;  /**< Set when a BAR0 address R/W falls into theaddress
06339                                                          range of the Packet-CSR, but for an unused
06340                                                          address. */
06341     uint64_t sprt3_err                    : 1;  /**< Reserved. */
06342     uint64_t sprt2_err                    : 1;  /**< Reserved. */
06343     uint64_t sprt1_err                    : 1;  /**< When an error response received on SLI port 1
06344                                                          this bit is set. */
06345     uint64_t sprt0_err                    : 1;  /**< When an error response received on SLI port 0
06346                                                          this bit is set. */
06347     uint64_t pins_err                     : 1;  /**< When a read error occurs on a packet instruction
06348                                                          this bit is set. */
06349     uint64_t pop_err                      : 1;  /**< When a read error occurs on a packet scatter
06350                                                          pointer pair this bit is set. */
06351     uint64_t pdi_err                      : 1;  /**< When a read error occurs on a packet data read
06352                                                          this bit is set. */
06353     uint64_t pgl_err                      : 1;  /**< When a read error occurs on a packet gather list
06354                                                          read this bit is set. */
06355     uint64_t pin_bp                       : 1;  /**< Packet input count has exceeded the WMARK.
06356                                                          See SLI_PKT_IN_BP */
06357     uint64_t pout_err                     : 1;  /**< Set when PKO sends packet data with the error bit
06358                                                          set. */
06359     uint64_t psldbof                      : 1;  /**< Packet Scatterlist Doorbell count overflowed. Which
06360                                                          doorbell can be found in DPI_PINT_INFO[PSLDBOF] */
06361     uint64_t pidbof                       : 1;  /**< Packet Instruction Doorbell count overflowed. Which
06362                                                          doorbell can be found in DPI_PINT_INFO[PIDBOF] */
06363     uint64_t reserved_38_47               : 10;
06364     uint64_t dtime                        : 2;  /**< Whenever SLI_DMAx_CNT[CNT] is not 0, the
06365                                                          SLI_DMAx_TIM[TIM] timer increments every SLI
06366                                                          clock.
06367                                                          DTIME[x] is set whenever SLI_DMAx_TIM[TIM] >
06368                                                          SLI_DMAx_INT_LEVEL[TIME].
06369                                                          DTIME[x] is normally cleared by clearing
06370                                                          SLI_DMAx_CNT[CNT] (which also clears
06371                                                          SLI_DMAx_TIM[TIM]). */
06372     uint64_t dcnt                         : 2;  /**< DCNT[x] is set whenever SLI_DMAx_CNT[CNT] >
06373                                                          SLI_DMAx_INT_LEVEL[CNT].
06374                                                          DCNT[x] is normally cleared by decreasing
06375                                                          SLI_DMAx_CNT[CNT]. */
06376     uint64_t dmafi                        : 2;  /**< DMA set Forced Interrupts. */
06377     uint64_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
06378     uint64_t mac2_int                     : 1;  /**< Interrupt from MAC2.
06379                                                          See PEM2_INT_SUM (enabled by PEM2_INT_ENB_INT) */
06380     uint64_t reserved_28_28               : 1;
06381     uint64_t m3_un_wi                     : 1;  /**< Reserved. */
06382     uint64_t m3_un_b0                     : 1;  /**< Reserved. */
06383     uint64_t m3_up_wi                     : 1;  /**< Reserved. */
06384     uint64_t m3_up_b0                     : 1;  /**< Reserved. */

06390                                                          See PEM1_INT_SUM (enabled by PEM1_INT_ENB_INT) */
06391     uint64_t mac0_int                     : 1;  /**< Interrupt from MAC0.
06392                                                          See PEM0_INT_SUM (enabled by PEM0_INT_ENB_INT) */

06394                                                          See CIU_INT33_SUM0, CIU_INT_SUM1
06395                                                          (enabled by CIU_INT33_EN0, CIU_INT33_EN1) */
06396     uint64_t mio_int0                     : 1;  /**< Interrupt from MIO for PORT 0.
06397                                                          See CIU_INT32_SUM0, CIU_INT_SUM1

06400                                                          from MAC 1. This occurs when the window registers

07483 /**
07484  * cvmx_sli_mac#_pf#_int_sum
07485  *
07486  * Interrupt summary register for a given PF. Indexed (MAC index) by SLI_PORT_E.
07487  * The fields in this register are set when an interrupt condition occurs; write 1 to clear.
07488  */
07489 union cvmx_sli_macx_pfx_int_sum {
07490     uint64_t u64;
07491     struct cvmx_sli_macx_pfx_int_sum_s {
07492 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07493     uint64_t pppf_err                     : 1;  /**< When an error response is received for a PF PP transaction read, this bit is set. */
07494     uint64_t ppvf_err                     : 1;  /**< When an error response is received for a VF PP transaction read, this bit is set.
07495                                                          A subsequent read to SLI_MAC()_PF()_PP_VF_INT is required to discover which VF.
07496                                                          Note: this will only ever be set for SR-IOV PF's: SLI_PORT_E::PEM0 PF0. */
07497     uint64_t pktpf_err                    : 1;  /**< This bit is set when any of the following events occur
07498                                                          1) An error response is received for PF packet transaction read.
07499                                                          2) A doorbell overflow for a ring associated with this PF occurs in
07500                                                             SLI_PKT()_INSTR_BAOFF_DBELL or SLI_PKT()_SLIST_BAOFF_DBELL.
07501                                                          3) A packet was received from PKO for ring X, SLI_PKT_GBL_CONTROL[NOPTR_D] = 0
07502                                                             and SLI_PKTX_SLIST_BAOFF_DBELL[DBELL] = 0. */
07503     uint64_t pktvf_err                    : 1;  /**< This bit is set when any of the following events occur
07504                                                          1) An error response is received for VF packet transaction read.
07505                                                          2) A doorbell overflow for a ring associated with a VF occurs in
07506                                                             SLI_PKT()_INSTR_BAOFF_DBELL or SLI_PKT()_SLIST_BAOFF_DBELL.
07507                                                          3) A packet was received from PKO for ring X, SLI_PKT_GBL_CONTROL[NOPTR_D] = 0
07508                                                             and SLI_PKTX_SLIST_BAOFF_DBELL[DBELL] = 0.
07509                                                          4) An illegal bar0 bar1 bar2 memory access from a VF occurs.
07510                                                          A subsequent read to SLI_MAC()_PF()_PKT_VF_INT is required to discover which VF.
07511                                                          Note: this will only ever be set for SR-IOV PF's: SLI_PORT_E::PEM0 PF0. */
07512     uint64_t dmapf_err                    : 1;  /**< When an error response is received for a PF DMA transaction read, this bit is set. */
07513     uint64_t dmavf_err                    : 1;  /**< When an error response is received for a VF DMA transaction read, this bit is set.
07514                                                          A subsequent read to SLI_MAC()_PF()_DMA_VF_INT is required to discover which VF.
07515                                                          Note: this will only ever be set for SR-IOV PF's: SLI_PORT_E::PEM0 PF0. */
07516     uint64_t vf_mbox                      : 1;  /**< When an VF wants to communicate to a PF it writes its SLI_PKT_PF_MBOX_SIG2 register
07517                                                          causing
07518                                                          this bit to be set.
07519                                                          A subsequent read to SLI_MAC()_PF()_MBOX_INT is required to discover which VF.
07520                                                          Note: this will only ever be set for SR-IOV PF's: SLI_PORT_E::PEM0 PF0. */
07521     uint64_t reserved_38_56               : 19;
07522     uint64_t dtime                        : 2;  /**< Whenever SLI_DMA()_CNT[CNT] is not 0, the SLI_DMA()_TIM[TIM] timer increments
07523                                                          every SLI clock. DTIME<x> is set whenever SLI_DMA()_TIM[TIM] >
07524                                                          SLI_DMA()_INT_LEVEL[TIME]. DTIME<x> is normally cleared by clearing
07525                                                          SLI_DMA()_CNT[CNT] (which also clears SLI_DMA()_TIM[TIM]). */
07526     uint64_t dcnt                         : 2;  /**< DCNT<x> is set whenever SLI_DMAx_CNT[CNT] > SLI_DMA()_INT_LEVEL[CNT]. DCNT<x> is
07527                                                          normally cleared by decreasing SLI_DMA()_CNT[CNT]. */
07528     uint64_t dmafi                        : 2;  /**< DMA set forced interrupts. Set by SLI/DPI after completing a DPI DMA
07529                                                          Instruction with DPI_DMA_INSTR_HDR_S[FI] set. */
07530     uint64_t reserved_12_31               : 20;
07531     uint64_t un_wi                        : 1;  /**< Received unsupported N-TLP for window register from MAC. This occurs when the window
07532                                                          registers are disabled and a window register access occurs.
07533                                                          This can only be set by a PF and not a VF access. */
07534     uint64_t un_b0                        : 1;  /**< Received unsupported N-TLP for Bar 0 from MAC. This occurs when the BAR 0 address space
07535                                                          is disabled.
07536                                                          This can only be set by a PF and not a VF access. */
07537     uint64_t up_wi                        : 1;  /**< Received unsupported P-TLP for window register from MAC. This occurs when the window
07538                                                          registers are disabled and a window register access occurs.
07539                                                          This can only be set by a PF and not a VF access. */
07540     uint64_t up_b0                        : 1;  /**< Received unsupported P-TLP for Bar 0 from MAC. This occurs when the BAR 0 address space
07541                                                          This can only be set by a PF and not a VF access. */
07542     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
07543     uint64_t ptime                        : 1;  /**< The preferred method to service PTIME interrupts is through MSIX rings.  This bit is only
07544                                                          used
07545                                                          for legacy code.
07546                                                          Packet timer has an interrupt. The specific rings can be found in SLI_PKT_TIME_INT. */
07547     uint64_t pcnt                         : 1;  /**< The preferred method to service PCNT interrupts is through MSIX rings.  This bit is only
07548                                                          used
07549                                                          for legacy code.
07550                                                          Packet counter has an interrupt. The specific rings can be found in SLI_PKT_CNT_INT. */
07551     uint64_t reserved_2_3                 : 2;
07552     uint64_t mio_int                      : 1;  /**< Interrupt from CIU for this PF. CIU can output an interrupt for each each MAC
07553                                                          included in the CIU_DEST_IO_E enumeration. SLI can send the CIU interrupt for a
07554                                                          MAC out its PF0. [MIO_INT] bits are copies of corresponding CIU3_DEST()_IO_INT[INTR]
07555                                                          bits.
07556                                                          [MIO_INT] cannot assert for SLI_PORT_E::SRIO0 PF0 and SLI_PORT_E::SRIO1 PF0. */
07557     uint64_t rml_to                       : 1;  /**< A read or write transfer to a RSL that did not complete within
07558                                                          SLI_WINDOW_CTL[TIME] coprocessor-clock cycles. */
07559 #else
07560     uint64_t rml_to                       : 1;
07561     uint64_t mio_int                      : 1;
07562     uint64_t reserved_2_3                 : 2;
07563     uint64_t pcnt                         : 1;
07564     uint64_t ptime                        : 1;
07565     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
07566     uint64_t up_b0                        : 1;
07567     uint64_t up_wi                        : 1;
07568     uint64_t un_b0                        : 1;
07569     uint64_t un_wi                        : 1;
07570     uint64_t reserved_12_31               : 20;
07571     uint64_t dmafi                        : 2;
07572     uint64_t dcnt                         : 2;
07573     uint64_t dtime                        : 2;
07574     uint64_t reserved_38_56               : 19;
07575     uint64_t vf_mbox                      : 1;
07576     uint64_t dmavf_err                    : 1;
07577     uint64_t dmapf_err                    : 1;
07578     uint64_t pktvf_err                    : 1;
07579     uint64_t pktpf_err                    : 1;
07580     uint64_t ppvf_err                     : 1;
07581     uint64_t pppf_err                     : 1;
07582 #endif
07583     } s;
07584     struct cvmx_sli_macx_pfx_int_sum_s    cn73xx;
07585     struct cvmx_sli_macx_pfx_int_sum_s    cn78xx;
07586     struct cvmx_sli_macx_pfx_int_sum_s    cnf75xx;

07590 /**
07591  * cvmx_sli_mac#_pf#_mbox_int
07592  *
07593  * When a VF to PF MBOX write occurs the appropriate bit is set.
07594  * Indexed by (MAC index) SLI_PORT_E.

07920 /**
07921  * cvmx_sli_mem_access_subid#
07922  *
07923  * These registers contains address index and control bits for access to memory from cores.
07924  *
07925  */
07926 union cvmx_sli_mem_access_subidx {
07927     uint64_t u64;
07928     struct cvmx_sli_mem_access_subidx_s {
07929 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07930     uint64_t reserved_60_63               : 4;
07931     uint64_t pvf                          : 16; /**< Selects the function number accessed by the reads/writes/atomics. DPI_DMA_FUNC_SEL_S
07932                                                          describes the format of this field. If [PVF]!=0, [PORT] must select a PCIe MAC that
07933                                                          supports more than one physical function and/or must select a PCIe MAC
07934                                                          with SR-IOV enabled. */
07935     uint64_t reserved_43_43               : 1;
07936     uint64_t zero                         : 1;  /**< Causes all byte read operations to be zero-length read operations. Returns 0s to the EXEC
07937                                                          for all read data. This must be zero for SRIO ports. */
07938     uint64_t port                         : 3;  /**< The MAC that the reads/writes/atomics are sent to. Enumerated by SLI_PORT_E. */
07939     uint64_t nmerge                       : 1;  /**< When set, no merging is allowed in this window. Applicable to writes only. */
07940     uint64_t esr                          : 2;  /**< Endian swap for read operations. ES<1:0> for read operations to this subID. ES<1:0> is the
07941                                                          endian-swap attribute for these MAC memory space read operations. Not used for write or
07942                                                          atomic operations.
07943                                                          Enumerated by SLI_ENDIANSWAP_E. */
07944     uint64_t esw                          : 2;  /**< Endian swap for write operations. ES<1:0> for write operations to this subID. ES<1:0> is
07945                                                          the endian-swap attribute for these MAC memory space write operations. Not used for reads
07946                                                          and IOBDMAs.
07947                                                          Enumerated by SLI_ENDIANSWAP_E. */
07948     uint64_t wtype                        : 2;  /**< Write type. ADDRTYPE<1:0> for write operations to this subID.
07949                                                          For PCIE:
07950                                                            * ADDRTYPE<0> is the relaxed-order attribute.
07951                                                            * ADDRTYPE<1> is the no-snoop attribute.
07952                                                          For SRIO:
07953                                                            * ADDRTYPE<1:0> help select an SRIO()_S2M_TYPE() entry.
07954                                                          Not used for reads and IOBDMAs. */
07955     uint64_t rtype                        : 2;  /**< Read type. ADDRTYPE<1:0> for read operations to this subID.
07956                                                          For PCIE:
07957                                                            * ADDRTYPE<0> is the relaxed-order attribute.
07958                                                            * ADDRTYPE<1> is the no-snoop attribute.
07959                                                          For SRIO:
07960                                                            * ADDRTYPE<1:0> help select an SRIO()_S2M_TYPE() entry.
07961                                                          Not used for writes and atomics. */
07962     uint64_t reserved_0_29                : 30;
07963 #else
07964     uint64_t reserved_0_29                : 30;
07965     uint64_t rtype                        : 2;
07966     uint64_t wtype                        : 2;
07967     uint64_t esw                          : 2;
07968     uint64_t esr                          : 2;
07969     uint64_t nmerge                       : 1;
07970     uint64_t port                         : 3;
07971     uint64_t zero                         : 1;
07972     uint64_t reserved_43_43               : 1;
07973     uint64_t pvf                          : 16;
07974     uint64_t reserved_60_63               : 4;
07975 #endif
07976     } s;
07977     struct cvmx_sli_mem_access_subidx_cn61xx {
07978 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07979     uint64_t reserved_43_63               : 21;
07980     uint64_t zero                         : 1;  /**< Causes all byte reads to be zero length reads.
07981                                                          Returns to the EXEC a zero for all read data.
07982                                                          This must be zero for sRIO ports. */
07983     uint64_t port                         : 3;  /**< Physical MAC Port that reads/writes to
07984                                                          this subid are sent to. Must be <= 1, as there are
07985                                                          only two ports present. */
07986     uint64_t nmerge                       : 1;  /**< When set, no merging is allowed in this window. */
07987     uint64_t esr                          : 2;  /**< ES<1:0> for reads to this subid.
07988                                                          ES<1:0> is the endian-swap attribute for these MAC
07989                                                          memory space reads. */
07990     uint64_t esw                          : 2;  /**< ES<1:0> for writes to this subid.
07991                                                          ES<1:0> is the endian-swap attribute for these MAC
07992                                                          memory space writes. */
07993     uint64_t wtype                        : 2;  /**< ADDRTYPE<1:0> for writes to this subid
07994                                                          For PCIe:
07995                                                          - ADDRTYPE<0> is the relaxed-order attribute
07996                                                          - ADDRTYPE<1> is the no-snoop attribute
07997                                                          For sRIO:
07998                                                          - ADDRTYPE<1:0> help select an SRIO*_S2M_TYPE*
07999                                                            entry */
08000     uint64_t rtype                        : 2;  /**< ADDRTYPE<1:0> for reads to this subid
08001                                                          For PCIe:
08002                                                          - ADDRTYPE<0> is the relaxed-order attribute
08003                                                          - ADDRTYPE<1> is the no-snoop attribute
08004                                                          For sRIO:
08005                                                          - ADDRTYPE<1:0> help select an SRIO*_S2M_TYPE*
08006                                                            entry */
08007     uint64_t ba                           : 30; /**< Address Bits <63:34> for reads/writes that use
08008                                                          this subid. */
08009 #else
08010     uint64_t ba                           : 30;
08011     uint64_t rtype                        : 2;
08012     uint64_t wtype                        : 2;
08013     uint64_t esw                          : 2;
08014     uint64_t esr                          : 2;
08015     uint64_t nmerge                       : 1;

08017     uint64_t zero                         : 1;
08018     uint64_t reserved_43_63               : 21;
08019 #endif

08022     struct cvmx_sli_mem_access_subidx_cn61xx cn63xxp1;

08028                                                          Returns to the EXEC a zero for all read data.
08029                                                          This must be zero for sRIO ports. */

08031                                                          this subid are sent to. Must be <= 1, as there are
08032                                                          only two ports present. */

08034     uint64_t esr                          : 2;  /**< ES<1:0> for reads to this subid.
08035                                                          ES<1:0> is the endian-swap attribute for these MAC
08036                                                          memory space reads. */
08037     uint64_t esw                          : 2;  /**< ES<1:0> for writes to this subid.
08038                                                          ES<1:0> is the endian-swap attribute for these MAC
08039                                                          memory space writes. */

08047                                                          - ADDRTYPE<1> is the no-snoop attribute */

08049                                                          this subid. */

08064     struct cvmx_sli_mem_access_subidx_cn68xx cn68xxp1;
08065     struct cvmx_sli_mem_access_subidx_cn61xx cn70xx;
08066     struct cvmx_sli_mem_access_subidx_cn61xx cn70xxp1;
08067     struct cvmx_sli_mem_access_subidx_cn73xx {
08068 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08069     uint64_t reserved_60_63               : 4;
08070     uint64_t pvf                          : 16; /**< Selects the function number accessed by the reads/writes/atomics. DPI_DMA_FUNC_SEL_S
08071                                                          describes the format of this field. If [PVF]!=0, [PORT] must select a PCIe MAC that
08072                                                          supports more than one physical function and/or must select a PCIe MAC
08073                                                          with SR-IOV enabled. */
08074     uint64_t reserved_43_43               : 1;

08079     uint64_t esr                          : 2;  /**< Endian swap for read operations. ES<1:0> for read operations to this subID. ES<1:0> is the
08080                                                          endian-swap attribute for these MAC memory space read operations. Not used for write or
08081                                                          atomic operations.
08082                                                          Enumerated by SLI_ENDIANSWAP_E. */
08083     uint64_t esw                          : 2;  /**< Endian swap for write operations. ES<1:0> for write operations to this subID. ES<1:0> is
08084                                                          the endian-swap attribute for these MAC memory space write operations. Not used for reads
08085                                                          and IOBDMAs.
08086                                                          Enumerated by SLI_ENDIANSWAP_E. */
08087     uint64_t wtype                        : 2;  /**< Write type. ADDRTYPE<1:0> for write operations to this subID.

08093                                                          * ADDRTYPE<1> is the no-snoop attribute.

08095     uint64_t ba                           : 30; /**< Bus address. Address bits<63:34> for read/write/atomic operations. */
08096 #else

08743     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
08744     uint64_t ciu_int                      : 8;  /**< Selects which bit in the SLI_MSI_RCV() (0-255) will be set when the value specified in
08745                                                          the MSI_INT of this register is received during a write operation to the SLI_PCIE_MSI_RCV
08746                                                          register. */
08747     uint64_t msi_int                      : 8;  /**< Selects the value that is received when the SLI_PCIE_MSI_RCV register is written. */
08748 #else
08749     uint64_t msi_int                      : 8;
08750     uint64_t ciu_int                      : 8;
08751     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
08752 #endif
08753     } s;
08754     struct cvmx_sli_msi_wr_map_s          cn61xx;
08755     struct cvmx_sli_msi_wr_map_s          cn63xx;
08756     struct cvmx_sli_msi_wr_map_s          cn63xxp1;
08757     struct cvmx_sli_msi_wr_map_s          cn66xx;
08758     struct cvmx_sli_msi_wr_map_s          cn68xx;
08759     struct cvmx_sli_msi_wr_map_s          cn68xxp1;

08769 
08770 /**
08771  * cvmx_sli_msix#_table_addr
08772  *
08773  * The MSI-X table cannot be burst read or written.
08774  *
08775  * The combination of all MSI-X Tables contain (64 + 4) entries - one per
08776  * ring plus one per PF. (i.e. 64 plus one per valid SLI_MAC()_PF()_INT_SUM
08777  * present.)
08778  *
08779  * The MSI-X table for an individual PF has SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[TRS]
08780  * entries for the rings associated to the PF (up to 64 max) plus one
08781  * more table entry for SLI_MAC()_PF()_INT_SUM. The
08782  * SLI_MAC()_PF()_INT_SUM-related MSI-X table entry is
08783  * always entry SLI_MSIX(SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[TRS])_TABLE_ADDR and
08784  * always present and valid. All earlier SLI_MSIX()_TABLE_ADDR entries
08785  * correspond to rings. When SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[NVFS]=0, SR-IOV
08786  * virtual functions cannot be used, and all SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[TRS]+1
08787  * entries in the PF MSI-X table are present and valid for use by the PF.
08788  * When SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[NVFS]!=0, SR-IOV virtual functions may
08789  * be used, and the first
08790  *   SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[NVFS]*SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[RPVF]
08791  * entries of the PF MSI-X table are present but not valid, and
08792  * should never be accessed by the PF.
08793  *
08794  * The MSI-X table for an individual VF has SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[RPVF]
08795  * entries (up to 8 max), all valid, one per ring that the VF owns.
08796  */
08797 union cvmx_sli_msixx_table_addr {
08798     uint64_t u64;
08799     struct cvmx_sli_msixx_table_addr_s {
08800 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08801     uint64_t addr                         : 64; /**< Message address. */
08802 #else
08803     uint64_t addr                         : 64;
08804 #endif
08805     } s;
08806     struct cvmx_sli_msixx_table_addr_s    cn73xx;
08807     struct cvmx_sli_msixx_table_addr_s    cn78xx;
08808     struct cvmx_sli_msixx_table_addr_s    cn78xxp1;
08809     struct cvmx_sli_msixx_table_addr_s    cnf75xx;
08810 };
08811 typedef union cvmx_sli_msixx_table_addr cvmx_sli_msixx_table_addr_t;

08881 /**
08882  * cvmx_sli_msix_pba0
08883  *
08884  * The MSI-X pending bit array cannot be burst read.
08885  * In SRIO-V mode, a VF will find its pending completion interrupts in bit
08886  * positions [(RPVF-1):0]. If RPVF<64, bits [63:RPVF] are returned as zero.
08887  *
08888  * Each VF can read their own pending completion interrupts based on the ring/VF
08889  * configuration. Therefore, a VF sees the PBA as smaller than what is shown below
08890  * (unless it owns all 64 entries).  Unassigned bits will return zeros.
08891  *
08892  * <pre>
08893  *    RPVF  Interrupts per VF   Pending bits returned
08894  *    ----  -----------------   ---------------------
08895  *      0            0          0
08896  *      1            1          MSG_PND0
08897  *      2            2          MSG_PND1  - MSG_PND0
08898  *      4            4          MSG_PND3  - MSG_PND0
08899  *      8            8          MSG_PND7  - MSG_PND0
08900  * </pre>
08901  *
08902  * If SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[TRS]=63 (i.e. 64 total DPI Packet Rings configured), a PF will
08903  * find its pending completion interrupts in bit positions [63:0]. When
08904  * SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[TRS]=63,
08905  * the PF will find its PCIe error interrupt in SLI_MSIX_PBA1, bit position 0.
08906  *
08907  * If SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[TRS]<63 (i.e. 0, 1, 2, 4, or 8 rings configured), a PF will find
08908  * its ring pending completion interrupts in bit positions [TNR:0]. It will find its PCIe
08909  * error interrupt in bit position [(TNR+1)]. Bits [63:(TNR+2)] are returned as zero.
08910  * When SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[TRS]<63, SLI_MSIX_PBA1 is not used and returns zeros.
08911  *
08912  * If SRIO-V Mode is off there is no virtual function support, but the PF can configure up to 65
08913  * entries (up to 64 DPI Packet Rings plus 1 PF ring) for itself.
08914  */
08915 union cvmx_sli_msix_pba0 {
08916     uint64_t u64;
08917     struct cvmx_sli_msix_pba0_s {
08918 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08919     uint64_t msg_pnd                      : 64; /**< VF message pending vector. */
08920 #else
08921     uint64_t msg_pnd                      : 64;
08922 #endif
08923     } s;
08924     struct cvmx_sli_msix_pba0_s           cn73xx;
08925     struct cvmx_sli_msix_pba0_s           cn78xx;
08926     struct cvmx_sli_msix_pba0_s           cn78xxp1;
08927     struct cvmx_sli_msix_pba0_s           cnf75xx;
08928 };
08929 typedef union cvmx_sli_msix_pba0 cvmx_sli_msix_pba0_t;
08930 
08931 /**
08932  * cvmx_sli_msix_pba1
08933  *
08934  * The MSI-X pending bit array cannot be burst read.
08935  *
08936  * PF_PND is assigned to PCIe related errors. The error bit can only be found in PBA1 when
08937  * SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[TRS]=63 (i.e. 64 total DPI Packet Rings configured).
08938  *
08939  * This register is accessible by the PF. A read by a particular PF only
08940  * returns its own pending status. That is, any PF can read this register, but the hardware
08941  * ensures
08942  * that the PF only sees its own status.
08943  */
08944 union cvmx_sli_msix_pba1 {
08945     uint64_t u64;
08946     struct cvmx_sli_msix_pba1_s {
08947 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08948     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
08949     uint64_t pf_pnd                       : 1;  /**< PF message pending. */
08950 #else
08951     uint64_t pf_pnd                       : 1;
08952     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
08953 #endif
08954     } s;
08955     struct cvmx_sli_msix_pba1_s           cn73xx;
08956     struct cvmx_sli_msix_pba1_s           cn78xx;
08957     struct cvmx_sli_msix_pba1_s           cn78xxp1;
08958     struct cvmx_sli_msix_pba1_s           cnf75xx;
08959 };
08960 typedef union cvmx_sli_msix_pba1 cvmx_sli_msix_pba1_t;

09131 /**
09132  * cvmx_sli_pkt#_cnts
09133  *
09134  * This register contains the counters for output rings.
09135  *
09136  */
09137 union cvmx_sli_pktx_cnts {
09138     uint64_t u64;
09139     struct cvmx_sli_pktx_cnts_s {
09140 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09141     uint64_t po_int                       : 1;  /**< Packet output interrupt bit for the ring. [PO_INT] reads as one whenever:
09142                                                           * [CNT]   > SLI_PKT()_INT_LEVELS[CNT].
09143                                                           * Or, [TIMER] > SLI_PKT()_INT_LEVELS[TIME].
09144                                                          [PO_INT] can cause an MSI-X interrupt for ring, and its [CNT] ([TIMER]) component
09145                                                          can cause SLI_MAC()_PF()_INT_SUM[PCNT] (SLI_MAC()_PF()_INT_SUM[PTIME]) to
09146                                                          be set if
09147                                                          SLI_PKT()_OUTPUT_CONTROL[CENB] (SLI_PKT()_OUTPUT_CONTROL[TENB]) is set.
09148                                                          SLI_PKT_CNT_INT (SLI_PKT_TIME_INT) shows the [CNT] ([TIMER]) component
09149                                                          for this and all other rings. See also SLI_PKT_IN_DONE()_CNTS[PO_INT]. */
09150     uint64_t pi_int                       : 1;  /**< Packet input interrupt bit for the ring. A copy of SLI_PKT_IN_DONE()_CNTS[PI_INT]. */
09151     uint64_t mbox_int                     : 1;  /**< Reads corresponding bit in SLI_PKT()_MBOX_INT. */
09152     uint64_t resend                       : 1;  /**< A write of 1 will resend an MSI-X interrupt message if there is a pending interrupt in
09153                                                          [P0_INT], [PI_INT] or [MBOX_INT] for this ring after the write of [CNT] occurs.
09154                                                          [RESEND] and [CNT] must be written together with the assumption that the write of
09155                                                          [CNT] will clear the [PO_INT] interrupt bit. If the write of [CNT] does not cause
09156                                                          the [CNT] to drop below the thresholds another MSI-X message will be sent.
09157                                                          The [RESEND] bit will never effect INTA/B/C/D or MSI interrupt. */
09158     uint64_t reserved_54_59               : 6;
09159     uint64_t timer                        : 22; /**< Timer, incremented every 1024 coprocessor-clock cycles when [CNT] is
09160                                                          not zero. The hardware clears both [TIMER] and [PO_INT] when [CNT]
09161                                                          goes to 0. The first increment of this count can occur between 0 to
09162                                                          1023 coprocessor-clock cycles after [CNT] becomes nonzero. */
09163     uint64_t cnt                          : 32; /**< Ring counter. Hardware adds to [CNT] as it sends packets out. On a write
09164                                                          to this register, hardware subtracts the amount written to the [CNT] field from
09165                                                          [CNT], which will clear [PO_INT] if [CNT] becomes <= SLI_PKT()_INT_LEVELS[CNT].
09166                                                          When SLI_PKT()_OUTPUT_CONTROL[BMODE] is clear, the hardware adds 1
09167                                                          to [CNT] per packet. When SLI_PKT()_OUTPUT_CONTROL[BMODE] is set, the hardware
09168                                                          adds (packet_length+X) to [CNT] per packet. X is zero when info pointer mode
09169                                                          is used, 8 when info pointer mode is not used. */
09170 #else
09171     uint64_t cnt                          : 32;
09172     uint64_t timer                        : 22;
09173     uint64_t reserved_54_59               : 6;
09174     uint64_t resend                       : 1;
09175     uint64_t mbox_int                     : 1;
09176     uint64_t pi_int                       : 1;
09177     uint64_t po_int                       : 1;
09178 #endif
09179     } s;
09180     struct cvmx_sli_pktx_cnts_cn61xx {
09181 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09182     uint64_t reserved_54_63               : 10;
09183     uint64_t timer                        : 22; /**< Timer incremented every 1024 core clocks
09184                                                          when SLI_PKTS#_CNTS[CNT] is non zero. Field
09185                                                          cleared when SLI_PKTS#_CNTS[CNT] goes to 0.
09186                                                          Field is also cleared when SLI_PKT_TIME_INT is
09187                                                          cleared.
09188                                                          The first increment of this count can occur
09189                                                          between 0 to 1023 core clocks. */

09194                                                          added to the register for each packet, when '1'

09197                                                          mode IS used the packet length is added to this

09241                                                           * [CNT]   > SLI_PKT(i)_INT_LEVELS[CNT], or
09242                                                           * [TIMER] > SLI_PKT(i)_INT_LEVELS[TIME]
09243                                                          [PO_INT] can cause an MSI-X interrupt for ring i, and its [CNT] ([TIMER]) component
09244                                                          can cause SLI_INT_SUM[PCNT] (SLI_INT_SUM[PTIME]) to be set if
09245                                                          SLI_PKT(i)_OUTPUT_CONTROL[CENB] (SLI_PKT(i)_OUTPUT_CONTROL[TENB]) is set.

09247                                                          for this and all other rings. See also SLI_PKT_IN_DONE(i)_CNTS[PO_INT]. */

09249     uint64_t reserved_61_54               : 8;

09251                                                          not zero. The hardware clears both [TIMER] and [PO_INT] when [CNT]
09252                                                          goes to 0. The first increment of this count can occur between 0 to
09253                                                          1023 coprocessor-clock cycles after [CNT] becomes nonzero. */
09254     uint64_t cnt                          : 32; /**< Ring counter. Hardware adds to [CNT] as it sends packets out. On a write
09255                                                          to this register, hardware subtracts the amount written to the [CNT] field from
09256                                                          [CNT], which will clear [PO_INT] if [CNT] becomes <= SLI_PKT(i)_INT_LEVELS[CNT].
09257                                                          When SLI_PKT()_OUTPUT_CONTROL[BMODE] is clear, the hardware adds 1
09258                                                          to [CNT] per packet. When SLI_PKT()_OUTPUT_CONTROL[BMODE] is set, the hardware
09259                                                          adds (packet_length+X) to [CNT] per packet. X is zero when info pointer mode

09357 /**

09359  *
09360  * This register is the control for read operations for gather list and instructions.
09361  *
09362  */

09366 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

09369                                                          Read only copy of SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[RPVF] */
09370     uint64_t reserved_31_47               : 17;
09371     uint64_t mac_num                      : 2;  /**< The MAC (PEM) that the physical function belongs to. Enumerated by SLI_PORT_E.
09372                                                          [MAC_NUM] is RO when accessed via BAR0 of a virtual function, and R/W otherwise.
09373                                                          [MAC_NUM] applies to the ring pair, which includes both this input
09374                                                          ring and to the output ring of the same index. */
09375     uint64_t quiet                        : 1;  /**< Asserted after a ring has gone into reset and the ring has met the conditions
09376                                                          of SLI_PKT_GBL_CONTROL[QTIME]. */
09377     uint64_t reserved_27_27               : 1;
09378     uint64_t rdsize                       : 2;  /**< Number of instructions to be read in one MAC read request. Two-bit values are:
09379                                                          0x0 = 1 instruction.
09380                                                          0x1 = 2 instructions.
09381                                                          0x2 = 3 instructions.
09382                                                          0x3 = 4 instructions. */
09383     uint64_t is_64b                       : 1;  /**< When IS_64B=1, instruction input ring i uses 64B versus 32B. */
09384     uint64_t rst                          : 1;  /**< Packet reset. When [RST]=1, the rings are in reset. [RST] can be set
09385                                                          by software writing a 1 to the field, by hardware upon receipt of an
09386                                                          FLR to an associated function, or by hardware when it receives an error
09387                                                          response for a read associated with the rings.
09388                                                          [RST] applies to both this input ring and to the output ring of the same
09389                                                          index.
09390                                                          Software must not clear [RST] from 1->0 until the [QUIET] bit is a 1.
09391                                                          A ring reset may clear all state associated with the input and
09392                                                          output rings, so software must completely re-initialize both
09393                                                          before reusing them.
09394                                                          See also SLI_PKT_RING_RST[RST]. */
09395     uint64_t enb                          : 1;  /**< Enable for the input ring i. Whenever [RST] is set, hardware forces
09396                                                          [ENB] clear.  Software can only write [ENB] to 1.  [ENB] can only be cleared
09397                                                          only by writing SLI_PKT()_INPUT_CONTROL[RST].  Once [ENB] is cleared software can
09398                                                          only write [ENB] to a 1 once [QUIET] is a 1.
09399                                                          In the PF, [ENB] is also SLI_PKT_INSTR_ENB<i>. */

09401     uint64_t d_nsr                        : 1;  /**< If [USE_CSR]=1 (DPTR Format 0), [D_NSR] is ADDRTYPE<1> for First Direct and

09403                                                          ADDRTYPE<1> helps select an SRIO()_S2M_TYPE() entry with sRIO.
09404                                                          If [USE_CSR]=0 (DPTR Format 1), [D_NSR] is MACADD<61> for First Direct and
09405                                                          Gather DPTR reads. (ADDRTYPE<1> comes from DPTR<61> in these cases when
09406                                                          [USE_CSR]=0.) */

09408                                                          DPTR reads. ES<1:0> is the endian-swap attribute for these MAC memory space
09409                                                          reads. Enumerated by SLI_ENDIANSWAP_E.
09410                                                          If [USE_CSR]=0 (DPTR Format 1), [D_NSR] is MACADD<63:62> for First Direct and
09411                                                          Gather DPTR reads. (ES<1:0> comes from DPTR<63:62> in these cases when
09412                                                          [USE_CSR]=0.) */

09414                                                          Gather DPTR reads. ADDRTYPE<0> is the relaxed-order attribute for PCIe. It helps
09415                                                          select an SRIO()_S2M_TYPE() entry with sRIO.
09416                                                          If [USE_CSR]=0 (DPTR Format 1), [D_NSR] is MACADD<60> for First Direct and
09417                                                          Gather DPTR reads. (ADDRTYPE<0> comes from DPTR<60> in these cases when
09418                                                          [USE_CSR]=0.) */
09419     uint64_t use_csr                      : 1;  /**< When set to 1, [D_ROR], [D_ESR], and [D_NSR] are used for ROR, ESR, and NSR,
09420                                                          respectively.
09421                                                          (DPTR Format 0) When clear to 0, <63:60> from a First Direct or Gather DPTR are
09422                                                          used.
09423                                                          (DPTR Format 1) The bits not used for ROR, ESR, and NSR become bits <63:60> of
09424                                                          the address used to fetch packet data. */
09425     uint64_t nsr                          : 1;  /**< [NSR] is ADDRTYPE<1> for input instruction reads (from
09426                                                          SLI_PKT()_INSTR_BADDR+) and First Indirect DPTR reads. ADDRTYPE<1>
09427                                                          is the no-snoop attribute for PCIe.

09430                                                          SLI_PKT()_INSTR_BADDR+) and First Indirect DPTR reads. ES<1:0> is
09431                                                          the endian-swap attribute for these MAC memory space reads.
09432                                                          Enumerated by SLI_ENDIANSWAP_E. */

09434                                                          SLI_PKT()_INSTR_BADDR+) and First Indirect DPTR reads.
09435                                                          ADDRTYPE<0> is the relaxed-order attribute for PCIe.
09436                                                          It helps select an SRIO()_S2M_TYPE() entry with sRIO. */
09437 #else
09438     uint64_t ror                          : 1;
09439     uint64_t esr                          : 2;
09440     uint64_t nsr                          : 1;
09441     uint64_t use_csr                      : 1;
09442     uint64_t d_ror                        : 1;

09451     uint64_t quiet                        : 1;
09452     uint64_t mac_num                      : 2;

09455     uint64_t reserved_55_63               : 9;
09456 #endif
09457     } s;

09552     uint64_t reserved_31_31               : 1;
09553     uint64_t pvf_num                      : 16;
09554     uint64_t rpvf                         : 7;
09555     uint64_t reserved_55_63               : 9;
09556 #endif
09557     } cn73xx;
09558     struct cvmx_sli_pktx_input_control_cn73xx cn78xx;
09559     struct cvmx_sli_pktx_input_control_cn78xxp1 {
09560 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09561     uint64_t reserved_39_63               : 25;
09562     uint64_t vf_num                       : 7;  /**< The function number that the ring belongs to. When [VF_NUM]=0, the physical
09563                                                          function controls the ring. When [VF_NUM]!=0, it must correctly indicate the
09564                                                          virtual function number that controls the ring. ([VF_NUM]=1 selects the first
09565                                                          virtual function within the selected physical function, [VF_NUM]=2 selects
09566                                                          the second virtual function within the selected physical function ...)
09567                                                          Legal values are 0..64.
09568                                                          [VF_NUM] is RO when accessed via BAR0 of a virtual function, and R/W otherwise.
09569                                                          [VF_NUM] applies to both this input ring and to the output ring of the same
09570                                                          index. */
09571     uint64_t reserved_31_31               : 1;
09572     uint64_t mac_num                      : 2;  /**< The MAC (PEM) that the physical function belongs to. Legal value are 0-3.
09573                                                          [MAC_NUM] is RO when accessed via BAR0 of a virtual function, and R/W otherwise.
09574                                                          [MAC_NUM] applies to both this input ring and to the output ring of the same
09575                                                          index. */
09576     uint64_t reserved_27_28               : 2;
09577     uint64_t rdsize                       : 2;  /**< Number of instructions to be read in one MAC read request for the 4 ports, 16 rings. Two
09578                                                          bit value are:
09579                                                          0x0 = 1 Instruction.
09580                                                          0x1 = 2 Instructions.
09581                                                          0x2 = 3 Instructions.
09582                                                          0x3 = 4 Instructions. */
09583     uint64_t is_64b                       : 1;  /**< When IS_64B=1, instruction input ring i uses 64B versus 32B. */
09584     uint64_t rst                          : 1;  /**< Packet reset. When [RST]=1, the rings are in reset. [RST] can be set
09585                                                          by software writing a 1 to the field, by hardware upon receipt of an
09586                                                          FLR to an associated function, or by hardware when it receives an error
09587                                                          response for a read associated with the rings.
09588                                                          [MAC_NUM] applies to both this input ring and to the output ring of the same
09589                                                          index.
09590                                                          Software must not clear [RST] from 1->0 until [RST] has been asserted
09591                                                          for at least 2ms. A ring reset may clear all state associated with the
09592                                                          input and output rings, so software must completely re-initialize both
09593                                                          before reusing them.
09594                                                          See also SLI_PKT_RING_RST[RST]. */
09595     uint64_t enb                          : 1;  /**< Enable for the input ring i. Whenever [RST] is set, hardware forces
09596                                                          [ENB] clear.
09597                                                          In the PF, [ENB] is also SLI_PKT_INSTR_ENB<i>. */
09598     uint64_t pbp_dhi                      : 13; /**< Not used by hardware, but may be cleared by hardware when [RST] is set. */
09599     uint64_t d_nsr                        : 1;  /**< If [USE_CSR]=1 (DPTR Format 0), [D_NSR] is ADDRTYPE<1> for First Direct and
09600                                                          Gather DPTR reads. ADDRTYPE<1> is the no-snoop attribute for PCIe.
09601                                                          If [USE_CSR]=0 (DPTR Format 1), [D_NSR] is MACADD<61> for First Direct and
09602                                                          Gather DPTR reads. (ADDRTYPE<1> comes from DPTR<61> in these cases when
09603                                                          [USE_CSR]=0.) */
09604     uint64_t d_esr                        : 2;  /**< If [USE_CSR]=1 (DPTR Format 0), [D_ESR] is ES<1:0> for First Direct and Gather
09605                                                          DPTR reads. ES<1:0> is the endian-swap attribute for these MAC memory space
09606                                                          reads. Enumerated by SLI_ENDIANSWAP_E.
09607                                                          If [USE_CSR]=0 (DPTR Format 1), [D_NSR] is MACADD<63:62> for First Direct and
09608                                                          Gather DPTR reads. (ES<1:0> comes from DPTR<63:62> in these cases when
09609                                                          [USE_CSR]=0.) */
09610     uint64_t d_ror                        : 1;  /**< If [USE_CSR]=1 (DPTR Format 0), [D_ROR] is ADDRTYPE<0> for First Direct and
09611                                                          Gather DPTR reads. ADDRTYPE<0> is the relaxed-order attribute for PCIe.
09612                                                          If [USE_CSR]=0 (DPTR Format 1), [D_NSR] is MACADD<60> for First Direct and
09613                                                          Gather DPTR reads. (ADDRTYPE<0> comes from DPTR<60> in these cases when
09614                                                          [USE_CSR]=0.) */
09615     uint64_t use_csr                      : 1;  /**< When set to 1, [D_ROR], [D_ESR], and [D_NSR] are used for ROR, ESR, and NSR,
09616                                                          respectively.
09617                                                          (DPTR Format 0) When clear to 0, <63:60> from a First Direct or Gather DPTR are
09618                                                          used.
09619                                                          (DPTR Format 1) The bits not used for ROR, ESR, and NSR become bits <63:60> of
09620                                                          the address used to fetch packet data. */
09621     uint64_t nsr                          : 1;  /**< [NSR] is ADDRTYPE<1> for input instruction reads (from
09622                                                          SLI_PKT()_INSTR_BADDR+) and First Indirect DPTR reads. ADDRTYPE<1>
09623                                                          is the no-snoop attribute for PCIe. */
09624     uint64_t esr                          : 2;  /**< [ESR] is ES<1:0> for input instruction reads (from
09625                                                          SLI_PKT()_INSTR_BADDR+) and First Indirect DPTR reads. ES<1:0> is
09626                                                          the endian-swap attribute for these MAC memory space reads.
09627                                                          Enumerated by SLI_ENDIANSWAP_E. */
09628     uint64_t ror                          : 1;  /**< [ROR] is ADDRTYPE<0> for input instruction reads (from
09629                                                          SLI_PKT()_INSTR_BADDR+) and First Indirect DPTR reads.
09630                                                          ADDRTYPE<0> is the relaxed-order attribute for PCIe. */
09631 #else
09632     uint64_t ror                          : 1;
09633     uint64_t esr                          : 2;
09634     uint64_t nsr                          : 1;
09635     uint64_t use_csr                      : 1;
09636     uint64_t d_ror                        : 1;
09637     uint64_t d_esr                        : 2;
09638     uint64_t d_nsr                        : 1;
09639     uint64_t pbp_dhi                      : 13;
09640     uint64_t enb                          : 1;
09641     uint64_t rst                          : 1;
09642     uint64_t is_64b                       : 1;
09643     uint64_t rdsize                       : 2;
09644     uint64_t reserved_27_28               : 2;
09645     uint64_t mac_num                      : 2;
09646     uint64_t reserved_31_31               : 1;
09647     uint64_t vf_num                       : 7;
09648     uint64_t reserved_39_63               : 25;
09649 #endif
09650     } cn78xxp1;
09651     struct cvmx_sli_pktx_input_control_cn73xx cnf75xx;
09652 };
09653 typedef union cvmx_sli_pktx_input_control cvmx_sli_pktx_input_control_t;

10133                                                          and (SLI_PKT(i)_CNTS[TIMER] > SLI_PKT(i)_INT_LEVELS[TIME]),

10141     uint64_t cenb                         : 1;  /**< SLI_MAC()_PF()_INT_SUM[PCNT] interrupt enable for this ring i. When [CENB] is set
10142                                                          and (SLI_PKT(i)_CNTS[CNT] > SLI_PKT(i)_INT_LEVELS[CNT]),

10144                                                          can occur if corresponding SLI_MAC()_PF()_INT_SUM[PCNT] is set.

10151                                                          is in buffer-pointer-only mode. */

10154                                                          ring. ES<1:0> is the endian-swap attribute for these MAC memory space writes.
10155                                                          If [DPTR]=0 (DPTR Format 1), [ES] is MACADD<63:62> for buffer/info write
10156                                                          operations to buffer/info pair MAC memory space addresses fetched from packet
10157                                                          output ring. (<63:62> of the buffer or info pointer is ES<1:0> for the writes in

10160                                                          operations to buffer/info pair MAC memory space addresses fetched from packet
10161                                                          output ring. ADDRTYPE<1> is the no-snoop attribute for PCIe.
10162                                                          If [DPTR]=0 (DPTR Format 1), [NSR] is MACADD<61> for buffer/info write
10163                                                          operations to buffer/info pair MAC memory space addresses fetched from packet
10164                                                          output ring. (<61> of the buffer or info pointer is ADDRTYPE<1> for the writes

10213 /**
10214  * cvmx_sli_pkt#_pf_vf_mbox_sig#
10215  *
10216  * These registers are used for communication of data from the PF to the VF and vice versa.
10217  *
10218  * There are two registers per ring, SIG(0) and SIG(1). The PF and VF, both, have read and
10219  * write access to these registers.
10220  *
10221  * For PF-to-VF ring interrupts, SLI_PKT(0..63)_MBOX_INT[MBOX_EN] must be set.
10222  * When [MBOX_EN] is set, writes from the PF to byte 0 of the SIG(0) register will cause
10223  * an interrupt by setting [MBOX_INT] in the corresponding ring address of
10224  * SLI_PKT()_MBOX_INT[MBOX_INT],
10225  * SLI_PKT_IN_DONE()_CNTS[MBOX_INT], and SLI_PKT()_CNTS[MBOX_INT].
10226  *
10227  * For VF-to-PF ring interrupt, SLI_MAC()_PF()_INT_ENB[VF_MBOX] must be set.
10228  * When [VF_MBOX] is set, write from the VF to byte 0 of the SIG(1) register will cause an
10229  * interrupt by setting ring address VF_INT field in corresponding SLI_MAC()_PF()_MBOX_INT
10230  * register,
10231  * which may cause an interrupt to occur through PF.
10232  *
10233  * Each PF and VF can only access the rings that it owns as programmed by
10234  * SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO.
10235  * The signaling is ring-based. If a VF owns more than one ring, it can ignore the other
10236  * rings' registers if not needed.
10237  */
10238 union cvmx_sli_pktx_pf_vf_mbox_sigx {
10239     uint64_t u64;
10240     struct cvmx_sli_pktx_pf_vf_mbox_sigx_s {
10241 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
10242     uint64_t data                         : 64; /**< Communication data from PF to VF. Writes to SLI_PKT()_PF_VF_MBOX_SIG(0)
10243                                                          in the corresponding VF. */
10244 #else
10245     uint64_t data                         : 64;
10246 #endif
10247     } s;
10248     struct cvmx_sli_pktx_pf_vf_mbox_sigx_s cn73xx;
10249     struct cvmx_sli_pktx_pf_vf_mbox_sigx_s cn78xx;
10250     struct cvmx_sli_pktx_pf_vf_mbox_sigx_s cnf75xx;
10251 };
10252 typedef union cvmx_sli_pktx_pf_vf_mbox_sigx cvmx_sli_pktx_pf_vf_mbox_sigx_t;
10253

10445 /**

10447  *
10448  * This register specifies which output packet rings are interrupting because of packet counters.
10449  * A bit set in this interrupt register will set a corresponding bit in SLI_PKT_INT and can
10450  * also cause SLI_MAC()_PF()_INT_SUM[PCNT] to be set if SLI_PKT()_OUTPUT_CONTROL[CENB] is set.
10451  * When read by a function, this register informs which rings owned by the function (0 to N,
10452  * N as large as 63) have this interrupt pending.
10453  */

10461 #endif

10467                                                          SLI sets PORT<i> whenever
10468                                                          SLI_PKTi_CNTS[CNT] > SLI_PKT_INT_LEVELS[CNT].
10469                                                          SLI_PKT_CNT_INT_ENB[PORT<i>] is the corresponding
10470                                                          enable. */
10471 #else

10474 #endif

10486                                                          whenever SLI_PKT(i)_CNTS[CNT] > SLI_PKT(i)_INT_LEVELS[CNT].
10487                                                          RING<i> is the CNT component of SLI_PKT(i)_CNTS[PO_INT]
