10799 /**
10800  * cvmx_sli_pkt_in_done#_cnts
10801  *
10802  * This register contains counters for instructions completed on input rings.
10803  *
10804  */
10805 union cvmx_sli_pkt_in_donex_cnts {
10806     uint64_t u64;
10807     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_in_donex_cnts_s {
10808 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
10809     uint64_t po_int                       : 1;  /**< "Returns a 1 when either the corresponding bit in SLI_PKT_TIME_INT[RING[\#]] or
10810                                                          SLI_PKT_CNT_INT[RING[\#]] is set." */
10811     uint64_t pi_int                       : 1;  /**< Packet input interrupt bit for the ring. The hardware sets [PI_INT] whenever it updates
10812                                                          [CNT<31:0>] and is greater then [WMARK][15:0] and [CINT_ENB] is set.
10813                                                          The hardware will clear [PI_INT] when [CNT] is less then or equal to [WMARK][15:0]
10814                                                          [PI_INT] can cause an MSI-X interrupt for the ring, but will never cause an INTA/B/C/D
10815                                                          nor MSI interrupt nor set any SLI_MAC()_PF()_INT_SUM bit. SLI_PKT_IN_INT is a
10816                                                          multi-ring version of [PI_INT], and [PI_INT] is one component of SLI_PKT_INT. See also
10817                                                          SLI_PKT()_CNTS[PI_INT]. */
10818     uint64_t mbox_int                     : 1;  /**< Reads corresponding bit in SLI_PKT()_MBOX_INT. */
10819     uint64_t resend                       : 1;  /**< A write of 1 will resend an MSI-X interrupt message if there is a pending interrupt in
10820                                                          [P0_INT], [PI_INT] or [MBOX_INT] for this ring after the write of [CNT] occurs.
10821                                                          [RESEND] and [CNT] must be written together with the assumption that the write of
10822                                                          [CNT] will clear the [PI_INT] interrupt bit. If the write of [CNT] does not cause
10823                                                          the [CNT] to drop below the thresholds another MSI-X message is sent.
10824                                                          The [RESEND] bit never affects INTA/B/C/D or MSI interrupts. */
10825     uint64_t reserved_49_59               : 11;
10826     uint64_t cint_enb                     : 1;  /**< Packet input interrupt enable bit for the ring. When [CINT_ENB] is set,
10827                                                          the hardware sets [PI_INT] whenever it updates [CNT] and it is greater
10828                                                          than [WMARK].
10829                                                          When [CINT_ENB] is clear, the hardware will never set [PI_INT]. */
10830     uint64_t wmark                        : 16; /**< Packet input interrupt watermark for the ring. If [CINT_ENB] is set
10831                                                          and WMARK does not equal 0xFFFF, the hardware sets [PI_INT] whenever
10832                                                          it updates [CNT][31:0] and it is greater than [16'b0,[WMARK][15:0]]. */
10833     uint64_t cnt                          : 32; /**< Packet input done count for the ring. The hardware increments [CNT] by one
10834                                                          after it finishes reading (from the remote host) an instruction from the ring
10835                                                          and all of its associated packet data.
10836                                                          If SLI_PKT_GBL_CONTROL[PICNT_D] is not set, when [CNT] is written, it will subtract
10837                                                          the value from [CNT]. */
10838 #else
10839     uint64_t cnt                          : 32;
10840     uint64_t wmark                        : 16;
10841     uint64_t cint_enb                     : 1;
10842     uint64_t reserved_49_59               : 11;
10843     uint64_t resend                       : 1;
10844     uint64_t mbox_int                     : 1;
10845     uint64_t pi_int                       : 1;
10846     uint64_t po_int                       : 1;
10847 #endif
10848     } s;

10853                                                          is completed. This field is incremented as the
10854                                                          last of the data is read from the MAC. */
10855 #else

10857     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
10858 #endif

10869                                                          is completed. This field is incremented as the
10870                                                          last of the data is read from the MAC. */
10871 #else

10880 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
10881     uint64_t po_int                       : 1;  /**< Packet output interrupt bit for the ring. A copy of SLI_PKT(i)_CNTS[PO_INT]. */
10882     uint64_t pi_int                       : 1;  /**< Packet input interrupt bit for the ring. The hardware sets [PI_INT] whenever it updates
10883                                                          [CNT<15:0>] to equal [WMARK] when CINT_ENB is set. Writing a 1 clears [PI_INT].
10884                                                          [PI_INT] can cause an MSI-X interrupt for the ring, but will never cause an INTA/B/C/D

10890                                                          set [PI_INT] whenever it updates [CNT<15:0>] to equal [WMARK]. When [CINT_ENB]

10893                                                          sets [PI_INT] whenever it updates [CNT<15:0>] to equal [WMARK]. */

10896                                                          and all of its associated packet data. */
10897 #else

10904 #endif

10961                                                          SLI_PKT_IN_DONE(i)_CNTS[PI_INT]. */
10962 #else
10963     uint64_t ring                         : 64;
10964 #endif
10965     } s;

11028 /**
11029  * cvmx_sli_pkt_input_control
11030  *
11031  * Control for reads for gather list and instructions.
11032  *
11033  */
11034 union cvmx_sli_pkt_input_control {
11035     uint64_t u64;
11036     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_input_control_s {
11037 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
11038     uint64_t prd_erst                     : 1;  /**< PRD Error Reset */
11039     uint64_t prd_rds                      : 7;  /**< PRD Reads Out */
11040     uint64_t gii_erst                     : 1;  /**< GII Error Reset */
11041     uint64_t gii_rds                      : 7;  /**< GII Reads Out */
11042     uint64_t reserved_41_47               : 7;
11043     uint64_t prc_idle                     : 1;  /**< PRC In IDLE */
11044     uint64_t reserved_24_39               : 16;
11045     uint64_t pin_rst                      : 1;  /**< Packet In Reset. When a gather-list read receives
11046                                                          an error this bit (along with SLI_INT_SUM[PGL_ERR])
11047                                                          is set. When receiveing a PGL_ERR interrupt the SW
11048                                                          should:
11049                                                          1. Wait 2ms to allow any outstanding reads to return
11050                                                             or be timed out.
11051                                                          2. Write a '0' to this bit.
11052                                                          3. Startup the packet input again (all previous
11053                                                             CSR setting of the packet-input will be lost). */
11054     uint64_t pkt_rr                       : 1;  /**< When set '1' the input packet selection will be
11055                                                          made with a Round Robin arbitration. When '0'
11056                                                          the input packet ring is fixed in priority,
11057                                                          where the lower ring number has higher priority. */
11058     uint64_t pbp_dhi                      : 13; /**< PBP_DHI replaces address bits that are used
11059                                                          for parse mode and skip-length when
11060                                                          SLI_PKTi_INSTR_HEADER[PBP]=1.
11061                                                          PBP_DHI becomes either MACADD<63:55> or MACADD<59:51>
11062                                                          for the instruction DPTR reads in this case.
11063                                                          The instruction DPTR reads are called
11064                                                          "First Direct" or "First Indirect" in the HRM.
11065                                                          When PBP=1, if "First Direct" and USE_CSR=0, PBP_DHI
11066                                                          becomes MACADD<59:51>, else MACADD<63:55>. */
11067     uint64_t d_nsr                        : 1;  /**< ADDRTYPE<1> or MACADD<61> for packet input data
11068                                                          reads.
11069                                                          D_NSR becomes either ADDRTYPE<1> or MACADD<61>
11070                                                          for MAC memory space reads of packet input data
11071                                                          fetched for any packet input ring.
11072                                                          ADDRTYPE<1> if USE_CSR=1, else MACADD<61>.
11073                                                          In the latter case, ADDRTYPE<1> comes from DPTR<61>.
11074                                                          ADDRTYPE<1> is the no-snoop attribute for PCIe
11075                                                          , helps select an SRIO*_S2M_TYPE* entry with sRIO. */
11076     uint64_t d_esr                        : 2;  /**< ES<1:0> or MACADD<63:62> for packet input data
11077                                                          reads.
11078                                                          D_ESR becomes either ES<1:0> or MACADD<63:62>
11079                                                          for MAC memory space reads of packet input data
11080                                                          fetched for any packet input ring.
11081                                                          ES<1:0> if USE_CSR=1, else MACADD<63:62>.
11082                                                          In the latter case, ES<1:0> comes from DPTR<63:62>.
11083                                                          ES<1:0> is the endian-swap attribute for these MAC
11084                                                          memory space reads. */
11085     uint64_t d_ror                        : 1;  /**< ADDRTYPE<0> or MACADD<60> for packet input data
11086                                                          reads.
11087                                                          D_ROR becomes either ADDRTYPE<0> or MACADD<60>
11088                                                          for MAC memory space reads of packet input data
11089                                                          fetched for any packet input ring.
11090                                                          ADDRTYPE<0> if USE_CSR=1, else MACADD<60>.
11091                                                          In the latter case, ADDRTYPE<0> comes from DPTR<60>.
11092                                                          ADDRTYPE<0> is the relaxed-order attribute for PCIe
11093                                                          , helps select an SRIO*_S2M_TYPE* entry with sRIO. */
11094     uint64_t use_csr                      : 1;  /**< When set '1' the csr value will be used for
11095                                                          ROR, ESR, and NSR. When clear '0' the value in
11096                                                          DPTR will be used. In turn the bits not used for
11097                                                          ROR, ESR, and NSR, will be used for bits [63:60]
11098                                                          of the address used to fetch packet data. */
11099     uint64_t nsr                          : 1;  /**< ADDRTYPE<1> for packet input instruction reads and
11100                                                          gather list (i.e. DPI component) reads from MAC
11101                                                          memory space.
11102                                                          ADDRTYPE<1> is the no-snoop attribute for PCIe
11103                                                          , helps select an SRIO*_S2M_TYPE* entry with sRIO. */
11104     uint64_t esr                          : 2;  /**< ES<1:0> for packet input instruction reads and
11105                                                          gather list (i.e. DPI component) reads from MAC
11106                                                          memory space.
11107                                                          ES<1:0> is the endian-swap attribute for these MAC
11108                                                          memory space reads. */
11109     uint64_t ror                          : 1;  /**< ADDRTYPE<0> for packet input instruction reads and
11110                                                          gather list (i.e. DPI component) reads from MAC
11111                                                          memory space.
11112                                                          ADDRTYPE<0> is the relaxed-order attribute for PCIe
11113                                                          , helps select an SRIO*_S2M_TYPE* entry with sRIO. */
11114 #else
11115     uint64_t ror                          : 1;
11116     uint64_t esr                          : 2;
11117     uint64_t nsr                          : 1;
11118     uint64_t use_csr                      : 1;
11119     uint64_t d_ror                        : 1;
11120     uint64_t d_esr                        : 2;
11121     uint64_t d_nsr                        : 1;
11122     uint64_t pbp_dhi                      : 13;
11123     uint64_t pkt_rr                       : 1;
11124     uint64_t pin_rst                      : 1;
11125     uint64_t reserved_24_39               : 16;

11132 #endif

11138     uint64_t pkt_rr                       : 1;  /**< When set '1' the input packet selection will be
11139                                                          made with a Round Robin arbitration. When '0'
11140                                                          the input packet ring is fixed in priority,
11141                                                          where the lower ring number has higher priority. */
11142     uint64_t pbp_dhi                      : 13; /**< PBP_DHI replaces address bits that are used
11143                                                          for parse mode and skip-length when

11145                                                          PBP_DHI becomes either MACADD<63:55> or MACADD<59:51>
11146                                                          for the instruction DPTR reads in this case.

11150                                                          becomes MACADD<59:51>, else MACADD<63:55>. */

11324 /**

11326  *
11327  * This register combines the SLI_PKT_CNT_INT, SLI_PKT_TIME_INT or SLI_PKT_IN_INT interrupt
11328  * registers. When read by a function, this register informs which rings owned by the function
11329  * (0 to N, N as large as 63) have an interrupt pending.
11330  */
11331 union cvmx_sli_pkt_int {
11332     uint64_t u64;
11333     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_int_s {
11334 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
11335     uint64_t ring                         : 64; /**< Multi-ring packet interrupt register. Each RING<i> is set whenever any
11336                                                          of these three conditions are true:
11337                                                           * SLI_PKT(i)_CNTS[CNT] > SLI_PKT(i)_INT_LEVELS[CNT] (i.e. SLI_PKT_CNT_INT<i>
11338                                                             is set),
11339                                                           * Or, SLI_PKT(i)_CNTS[TIMER] > SLI_PKT(i)_INT_LEVELS[TIME] (i.e. SLI_PKT_TIME_INT<i>
11340                                                             is set).

11342                                                          Any of these three conditions can cause an MSI-X interrupt, but only
11343                                                          the first two (i.e. SLI_PKT_CNT_INT and SLI_PKT_TIME_INT) can cause
11344                                                          INTA/B/C/D and MSI interrupts.
11345                                                          SLI_PKT(i)_OUTPUT_CONTROL[CENB,TENB] have no effect on RING<i>. */
11346 #else
11347     uint64_t ring                         : 64;
11348 #endif
11349     } s;

11422 /**
11423  * cvmx_sli_pkt_mac#_pf#_rinfo
11424  *
11425  * This register sets the total number and starting number of rings for a given MAC and PF
11426  * combination. Indexed by (MAC index) SLI_PORT_E. In SR-IOV mode, SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[RPVF]
11427  * and SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[NVFS] must be non zero and determine which rings the PFs and
11428  * VFs own.
11429  *
11430  * An individual VF will own SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[RPVF] number of rings.
11431  *
11432  * A PF will own the rings starting from ((SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[SRN] +
11433  * (SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[RPVF] * SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[NVFS]))
11434  * to (SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[SRN] + (SLI_PKT_MAC()_PF()_RINFO[TRS] -
11435  * 1)). SLI_PKT()_INPUT_CONTROL[PVF_NUM] must be written to values that
11436  * correlate with the fields in this register.
11437  *
11438  * e.g. Given:
11439  * _ SLI_PKT_MAC0_PF0_RINFO[SRN] = 32,
11440  * _ SLI_PKT_MAC0_PF0_RINFO[TRS] = 32,
11441  * _ SLI_PKT_MAC0_PF0_RINFO[RPVF] = 4,
11442  * _ SLI_PKT_MAC0_PF0_RINFO[NVFS] = 7:
11443  * _ rings owned by VF1: 32,33,34,35
11444  * _ rings owned by VF2: 36,37,38,39
11445  * _ rings owned by VF3: 40,41,42,43
11446  * _ rings owned by VF4: 44,45,46,47
11447  * _ rings owned by VF5: 48,49,50,51
11448  * _ rings owned by VF6: 52,53,54,55
11449  * _ rings owned by VF7: 56,57,58,59
11450  * _ rings owned by PF:  60,61,62,63
11451  */
11452 union cvmx_sli_pkt_macx_pfx_rinfo {
11453     uint64_t u64;
11454     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_macx_pfx_rinfo_s {
11455 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
11456     uint64_t reserved_55_63               : 9;
11457     uint64_t nvfs                         : 7;  /**< The number of VFs for this PF. This field must not be zero whenever RPVF != 0.
11458                                                          Legal values are 0 to 64, with the requirement of (NVFS * RPVF) <= TRS. */
11459     uint64_t reserved_40_47               : 8;
11460     uint64_t rpvf                         : 8;  /**< The number of rings assigned to a VF for this PF. Legal values are 0 to 8
11461                                                          with the requirement of (NVFS * RPVF) <= TRS. */
11462     uint64_t reserved_24_31               : 8;
11463     uint64_t trs                          : 8;  /**< The number of rings assigned to the PF. Legal value are 0 to 64. */
11464     uint64_t reserved_7_15                : 9;
11465     uint64_t srn                          : 7;  /**< The starting ring number used by the PF. Legal value are 0 to 63. */
11466 #else
11467     uint64_t srn                          : 7;
11468     uint64_t reserved_7_15                : 9;
11469     uint64_t trs                          : 8;
11470     uint64_t reserved_24_31               : 8;
11471     uint64_t rpvf                         : 8;
11472     uint64_t reserved_40_47               : 8;
11473     uint64_t nvfs                         : 7;
11474     uint64_t reserved_55_63               : 9;
11475 #endif
11476     } s;
11477     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_macx_pfx_rinfo_s  cn73xx;
11478     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_macx_pfx_rinfo_s  cn78xx;
11479     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_macx_pfx_rinfo_s  cnf75xx;
11480 };
11481 typedef union cvmx_sli_pkt_macx_pfx_rinfo cvmx_sli_pkt_macx_pfx_rinfo_t;
11482 
11483 /**
11484  * cvmx_sli_pkt_mac#_rinfo
11485  *
11486  * This register sets the total number and starting number of rings used by the MAC.
11487  * This register is PF-only.
11488  */
11489 union cvmx_sli_pkt_macx_rinfo {
11490     uint64_t u64;
11491     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_macx_rinfo_s {
11492 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
11493     uint64_t reserved_40_63               : 24;

11495     uint64_t reserved_24_31               : 8;
11496     uint64_t trs                          : 8;  /**< The number of rings assigned to the MAC. Legal value are 0 to 64. */
11497     uint64_t reserved_7_15                : 9;

12244 /**
12245  * cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int
12246  *
12247  * This register specifies which output packets rings are interrupting because of packet timers.
12248  * A bit set in this interrupt register will set a corresponding bit in SLI_PKT_INT and can
12249  * also cause SLI_MAC()_PF()_INT_SUM[PTIME] to be set if
12250  * SLI_PKT()_OUTPUT_CONTROL[TENB]
12251  * is set. When read by a function, this register informs which rings owned by the function (0 to
12252  * N,
12253  * N as large as 63) have this interrupt pending.
12254  */
12255 union cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int {
12256     uint64_t u64;
12257     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int_s {
12258 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
12259     uint64_t reserved_0_63                : 64;
12260 #else
12261     uint64_t reserved_0_63                : 64;
12262 #endif
12263     } s;
12264     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int_cn61xx {
12265 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
12266     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
12267     uint64_t port                         : 32; /**< Output ring packet timer interrupt bits
12268                                                          SLI sets PORT<i> whenever
12269                                                          SLI_PKTi_CNTS[TIMER] > SLI_PKT_INT_LEVELS[TIME].
12270                                                          SLI_PKT_TIME_INT_ENB[PORT<i>] is the corresponding
12271                                                          enable. */
12272 #else
12273     uint64_t port                         : 32;
12274     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
12275 #endif
12276     } cn61xx;
12277     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int_cn61xx   cn63xx;
12278     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int_cn61xx   cn63xxp1;
12279     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int_cn61xx   cn66xx;
12280     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int_cn61xx   cn68xx;
12281     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int_cn61xx   cn68xxp1;
12282     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int_cn61xx   cn70xx;
12283     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int_cn61xx   cn70xxp1;
12284     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int_cn73xx {
12285 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
12286     uint64_t ring                         : 64; /**< Multi-ring output ring packet time interrupt bits. RING<i> reads as one
12287                                                          whenever SLI_PKT(i)_CNTS[TIMER] > SLI_PKT(i)_INT_LEVELS[TIME].
12288                                                          RING<i> is the TIMER component of SLI_PKT(i)_CNTS[PO_INT]
12289                                                          (and SLI_PKT_IN_DONE(i)_CNTS[PO_INT]), and one of the components
12290                                                          of SLI_PKT_INT[RING<i>]. Hardware may not update RING<i> when
12291                                                          software modifies SLI_PKT(i)_INT_LEVELS[TIME] - refer to the
12292                                                          description of SLI_PKT()_INT_LEVELS[TIME].
12293                                                          SLI_PKT(i)_OUTPUT_CONTROL[TENB] does not affect RING<i>. */
12294 #else
12295     uint64_t ring                         : 64;
12296 #endif
12297     } cn73xx;
12298     struct cvmx_sli_pkt_time_int_cn73xx   cn78xx;

12338 /**
12339  * cvmx_sli_port#_pkind
12340  *
12341  * SLI_PORT[0..31]_PKIND = SLI Port Pkind
12342  *
12343  * The SLI/DPI supports 32 input rings for fetching input packets. This register maps the input-rings (0-31) to a PKIND.
12344  */
12345 union cvmx_sli_portx_pkind {
12346     uint64_t u64;
12347     struct cvmx_sli_portx_pkind_s {
12348 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
12349     uint64_t reserved_25_63               : 39;
12350     uint64_t rpk_enb                      : 1;  /**< Alternate PKT_INST_HDR PKind Enable for this ring.
12351                                                          When RPK_ENB==1 and DPI prepends
12352                                                          a PKT_INST_HDR to a packet, the pkind for the
12353                                                          packet is PKINDR (rather than PKIND), and any
12354                                                          special PIP/IPD processing of the DPI packet is
12355                                                          disabled (see PIP_PRT_CFG*[INST_HDR,HIGIG_EN]).
12356                                                          (DPI prepends a PKT_INST_HDR when either
12357                                                          DPI_INST_HDR[R]==1 for the packet or
12358                                                          SLI_PKT*_INSTR_HEADER[USE_IHDR]==1 for the ring.)
12359                                                          When RPK_ENB==0, PKIND is the pkind for all
12360                                                          packets through the input ring, and
12361                                                          PIP/IPD will process a DPI packet that has a
12362                                                          PKT_INST_HDR specially. */
12363     uint64_t reserved_22_23               : 2;
12364     uint64_t pkindr                       : 6;  /**< Port Kind For this Ring used with packets
12365                                                          that include a DPI-prepended PKT_INST_HDR
12366                                                          when RPK_ENB is set. */
12367     uint64_t reserved_14_15               : 2;
12368     uint64_t bpkind                       : 6;  /**< Back-pressure pkind for this Ring. */
12369     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
12370     uint64_t pkind                        : 6;  /**< Port Kind For this Ring. */
12371 #else
12372     uint64_t pkind                        : 6;
12373     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
12374     uint64_t bpkind                       : 6;
12375     uint64_t reserved_14_15               : 2;
12376     uint64_t pkindr                       : 6;
12377     uint64_t reserved_22_23               : 2;
12378     uint64_t rpk_enb                      : 1;
12379     uint64_t reserved_25_63               : 39;
12380 #endif
12381     } s;
12382     struct cvmx_sli_portx_pkind_s         cn68xx;
12383     struct cvmx_sli_portx_pkind_cn68xxp1 {
12384 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
12385     uint64_t reserved_14_63               : 50;
12386     uint64_t bpkind                       : 6;  /**< Back-pressure pkind for this Ring. */
12387     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
12388     uint64_t pkind                        : 6;  /**< Port Kind For this Ring. */
12389 #else
12390     uint64_t pkind                        : 6;
12391     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
12392     uint64_t bpkind                       : 6;
12393     uint64_t reserved_14_63               : 50;
12394 #endif
12395     } cn68xxp1;

12469 /**

12471  *
12472  * These registers contain control for access from SLI to a MAC port. Indexed by SLI_PORT_E.
12473  * Write operations to these registers are not ordered with write/read operations to the MAC
12474  * memory space. To ensure that a write operation has completed, read the register before
12475  * making an access (i.e. MAC memory space) that requires the value of this register to be
12476  * updated.
12477  */

12484     uint64_t lcl_node                     : 1;  /**< Must be zero. */
12485     uint64_t wind_d                       : 1;  /**< Window disable. When set to 1, disables access to the window registers from the MAC port. */

12487                                                          address offsets:

12491                                                            SLI_WIN_WR_MASK,

12498                                                            SLI_CIU_INT_ENB,
12499                                                            SLI_MAC()_PF()_FLR_VF_INT,
12500                                                            SLI_MEM_ACCESS_SUBID(),
12501                                                            SLI_PP_PKT_CSR_CONTROL,
12502                                                            SLI_WINDOW_CTL,
12503                                                            SLI_MEM_ACCESS_CTL,
12504                                                            SLI_CTL_STATUS,
12505                                                            SLI_BIST_STATUS,
12506                                                            SLI_MEM_INT_SUM,
12507                                                            SLI_MEM_CTL,
12508                                                            SLI_CTL_PORT(),
12509                                                            SLI_PKT_MEM_CTL.
12510                                                          If [BAR0_D] is set, [WIND_D] should also be set. */
12511     uint64_t reserved_0_2                 : 3;
12512 #else
12513     uint64_t reserved_0_2                 : 3;

12525                                                          Registers from the MAC-Port.
12526                                                          When Authenticate-Mode is set the reset value of
12527                                                          this field is "1" else "0'. */
12528     uint64_t bar0_d                       : 1;  /**< When set '1' disables access from MAC to
12529                                                          BAR-0 address offsets: Less Than 0x330,
12530                                                          0x3CD0, and greater than 0x3D70 excluding
12531                                                          0x3e00.
12532                                                          When Authenticate-Mode is set the reset value of
12533                                                          this field is "1" else "0'. */

12535                                                                  0 = 128B

12537                                                                  2 = 512B
12538                                                                  3 = 1024B
12539                                                                  4 = 2048B
12540                                                                  5-7 = Reserved
12541                                                          This field should not exceed the desired
12542                                                                max read request size. This field is used to
12543                                                                determine if an IOBDMA is too large.
12544                                                          For a PCIe MAC, this field should not exceed
12545                                                                PCIE*_CFG030[MRRS].
12546                                                          For a sRIO MAC, this field should indicate a size
12547                                                                of 256B or smaller. */
12548 #else
12549     uint64_t mrrs                         : 3;
12550     uint64_t bar0_d                       : 1;
12551     uint64_t wind_d                       : 1;
12552     uint64_t reserved_5_63                : 59;
12553 #endif

12875 /**
12876  * cvmx_sli_tx_pipe
12877  *
12878  * SLI_TX_PIPE = SLI Packet TX Pipe
12879  *
12880  * Contains the starting pipe number and number of pipes used by the SLI packet Output.
12881  * If a packet is recevied from PKO with an out of range PIPE number, the following occurs:
12882  * - SLI_INT_SUM[PIPE_ERR] is set.
12883  * - the out of range pipe value is used for returning credits to the PKO.
12884  * - the PCIe packet engine will treat the PIPE value to be equal to [BASE].
12885  */
12886 union cvmx_sli_tx_pipe {
12887     uint64_t u64;
12888     struct cvmx_sli_tx_pipe_s {
12889 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
12890     uint64_t reserved_24_63               : 40;
12891     uint64_t nump                         : 8;  /**< Number of pipes the the SLI/DPI supports.
12892                                                          When this value is 4 or less there is a performance
12893                                                          advantage for output packets.
12894                                                          The SLI/DPI can support up to 32 pipes assigned to
12895                                                          packet-rings 0 - 31. */
12896     uint64_t reserved_7_15                : 9;
12897     uint64_t base                         : 7;  /**< When NUMP is non-zero, indicates the base pipe
12898                                                          number the SLI/DPI will accept.
12899                                                          The SLI/DPI will accept pko packets from pipes in
12900                                                          the range of:
12901                                                            BASE .. (BASE+(NUMP-1))
12902                                                          BASE and NUMP must be constrained such that
12903                                                            1) BASE+(NUMP-1) < 127
12904                                                            2) Each used PKO pipe must map to exactly
12905                                                               one ring. Where BASE == ring 0, BASE+1 == to
12906                                                               ring 1, etc
12907                                                            3) The pipe ranges must be consistent with
12908                                                               the PKO configuration. */
12909 #else
12910     uint64_t base                         : 7;
12911     uint64_t reserved_7_15                : 9;
12912     uint64_t nump                         : 8;
12913     uint64_t reserved_24_63               : 40;
12914 #endif
12915     } s;
12916     struct cvmx_sli_tx_pipe_s             cn68xx;
12917     struct cvmx_sli_tx_pipe_s             cn68xxp1;
12918 };
